Hi @renukamanavalan , 

- From the jsonpatch website (https://extendsclass.com/json-patch.html), it recognizes the difference when we change the ip from lowercase to uppercase.

```
Source JSON:
{
 "INTERFACE": {
 "Ethernet64|FC00::41~1126": {}
 }
}

Target JSON:
{
 "INTERFACE": {
 "Ethernet64|fc00::41~1126": {}
 }
}

JSON Patch
[
 {
 "op": "remove",
 "path": "/LOOPBACK_INTERFACE/Loopback0|FC00:1::32~1128"
 },
 {
 "op": "add",
 "path": "/LOOPBACK_INTERFACE/Loopback0|fc00:1::32~1128",
 "value": {}
 }
]

```

- Another thing is that it was UPPERCASE at first, but it was modified to LOWERCASE by unknown operation. Here is the log

```
 "stdout_lines":[
====>#####NOTE: Where does it come of below line conversion? ######
 "converted ipv6 address to lowercase fc00::41~1126 with prefix /INTERFACE/Ethernet64| in value: /INTERFACE/Ethernet64|FC00::41~1126",
 "Patch Applier: Patch application starting.",
```
I think it is good if we can prevent that operation.
Need to mention in test `generic_patch_add_t0`, it doesn't do the conversion.
